So in the course of trying to sort out my MPI issues with cwltool, I was debugging my schema a bit and am now very confused about naming of things. The AVRO spec( https://avro.apache.org/docs/current/spec.html#names) says that names are valid C identifiers and that a full name (namespace + name) is a .-separated list of such names.

However (at least as used by cwltool) full names are allowed to be URIs. 
Here in salad, I added to my code (#324 ) a further check to the `validate` function:
```python
class Name(object):
    """Class to describe Avro name."""
    # AVRO docs sayeth that a valid name must start with [A-Za-z_] and
    # subsequently contain only [A-Za-z0-9_]
    _avro_name_re = re.compile(r"^[A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*$")
    @classmethod
    def _is_avro_name(cls, s : str) -> bool:
        return cls._avro_name_re.match(s) is not None
    # Further they say that a namespace is a .-separated sequence of
    # names and a full name is [namespace.]name
    @classmethod
    def _is_avro_fullname(cls, s: str) -> bool:
        return all(cls._is_avro_name(part) for part in s.split("."))
    def __init__(self, name_attr, space_attr, default_space):
        # Ensure valid ctor args
        def validate(val, name):
            if val is None:
                return
            if isinstance(val, str) and val != "":
                if not self._is_avro_fullname(val):
                    breakpoint()
                    raise SchemaParseException("Not a valid AVRO name '{}'".format(val))
                return
            fail_msg = "{} must be non-empty string or None.".format(name)
            raise SchemaParseException(fail_msg)
        validate(name_attr, "Name")
        validate(space_attr, "Space")
        validate(default_space, "Default space")
```

Which fails on the name `'http://commonwl.org/cwltool#LoadListingRequirement`

TBH, I'm a bit out of my depth here with the spec, but the code of `Name.get_space` makes it clear that it expects an Avro name (or minor extension). I wonder if there's some elision (in the code at least) of the difference between an identifier and an Avro name?

